MENINGITIS - ETHIOPIA: MIXED ETIOLOGY, LOW CASE FATALITY RATE, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 6 Apr 2022
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/ethiopia-meningitis-outbreak-called-concerning-19833/


Since the week ending [12 Dec 2021], Ethiopia has seen a total of 1398 suspected meningitis cases with 13 deaths (case fatality ratio (CFR) 0.9%) reported from 11 out of 12 regions in the country.

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), since the beginning of the outbreak in the country, 4 regions (Oromia, Somali, SNNPR [Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region], Amhara) crossed the epidemic threshold and 5 regions (Harari, Afar, Addis Ababa, Benishangul-Gumuz, and Gambella) crossed the alert threshold.

The UN agency says the ongoing meningitis outbreak in Ethiopia is concerning as the country is responding to multiple disease outbreaks, natural disasters, and humanitarian crisis.

Ethiopia is one of the African countries affected by both armed conflict and natural disasters (drought, disease outbreaks) including the ongoing meningitis outbreak. Although a relatively low CFR has been recorded for the meningitis outbreak, it is important that the necessary actions are implemented for its control and to prevent any deterioration. A mixed etiology (bacterial and viral) has been identified so far, yet the total number of samples analyzed is relatively low. More sample collection and analysis are needed to identify the dominant pathogen and request the appropriate vaccine for response.

[byline: Robert Herriman]

